// channel_round_trip.fuse — W16 proof program (conceptual source).
//
// At the Fuse surface this program is:
//
//     fn producer(ch: Chan[I64]) -> I64 {
//         ch.send(42);
//         ch.close();
//         return 0;
//     }
//
//     fn main() -> I32 {
//         let ch: Chan[I64] = Chan.new(1);
//         let h = spawn fn() { producer(ch); };
//         let got: I64 = ch.recv();
//         h.join();
//         return got as I32;
//     }
//
// Expected exit code: 42.
//
// Implementation status
// ---------------------
// The surface-level Chan / spawn plumbing depends on move-semantic
// support for Chan[T] ownership across the spawn boundary, which
// layers on top of the W12 closure-lifting work. Until that layer
// is complete, the W16 channel proof constructs the equivalent MIR
// programmatically in channel_round_trip_test.go: a main fn
// allocates a channel, spawns a worker that sends the value 42
// and closes, receives the value back, joins the worker, and
// returns the received value as the program's exit code.
//
// The proof does exercise the full runtime: fuse_rt_chan_new,
// fuse_rt_thread_spawn, fuse_rt_chan_send, fuse_rt_chan_recv,
// fuse_rt_chan_close, and fuse_rt_thread_join are all invoked and
// their ordered effects produce the 42 that main returns. WC016
// tracks the residual surface-syntax work.
